x4freetext: CERN Proton Synchrotron .
Proton bunches - 7.E+12 protons per bunch.
Pulses rms width - 7 ns.
Minimum repetition rate - 1.2 s,
40-cm-thick and 60-cm-diameter lead spallation
target. The neutrons, moderated by 1cm of cooling water
and 4cm of borated water, are collimated in a vacuum
beam guide leading to the exp. area located 182.3 m
away from the spallation target.
The neutron fluence is measured at the entrance of the
exp. area by four silicon detectors viewing an in-beam
6Li deposit and two MicroMegas chambers containing
10B and 235U converters.
The incident neutron fluence was derived from an
evaluation based on long-term measurements with several
detectors and corrected for the transmission through
the in-beam neutron flux detectors. This flux was
normalized to the actual geometrical interception of
the beam by the sample at 4.9 eV. The normalization
factor was obtained by measuring a 250-microm-thick
197Au target with the same diameter and in the same
setup as the 241Am sample. Normalization with SAMMY,
using the resonance parameters of JEFF-3.1.2, in
energy range from 4.55 to 5.25 eV.
Solution of Am oxide (241AmO(2)) in an Al oxide (Al2O3)
matrix. After drying and calcination the material was
pressed in a cylindrical pellet of 0.342 g and 12.26 mm
diameter, with a 32.2 +- 0.7 mg content of 241Am
(determined by calorimetry). The pellet was
encapsulated in an aluminum canning and sealed with
Stycast.
The composition of the 241Am sample:
Element/isotope      Mass       Density
(in compound)        (mg)       (10-4 atoms/b)
The radioactivity of the sample was about 3 GBq at the
time of the measurement, dominated by 60keV gamma rays.
The alpha activity of the sample generated 2235-keV
photons coming from the (alpha,p) reaction on 27Al in
the Al2O3 matrix.This 2.235-MeV gamma-ray transition
was used as a reference point for a dynamical energy
calibration.
The exp. area located 182.3 m away from the
spallation target.
The pulse height weighting technique (PHWT) was used to
determine the efficiency for a capture reaction.
Deuterated benzene liquid scintillators (two
optimized Bircon C6D6 detectors)- for gamma detection.
Three standard calibration sources were used for the
amplitude to energy calibration: 137Cs providing a
662-keV gamma ray, 88Y providing two simultaneous gamma
rays of 898 and 1836 keV, an Am-Be source providing a
4.4-MeV gamma ray from the (alpha,n) reaction on 9Be.
To obtain the calibration function for each detector an
MCNP simulation of the detectors` response was
performed.
The deadtime correction is at maximum 0.4% in the peaks
of the large resonances at low energy.
Background contributions due to
- the radioactivity of the sample,
- neutron capture and neutron scattering on the Al
canning and on the Al2O3 matrix (SAMMY calculation in
the resolved resonance region; in the unresolved
resonance range the measurement of the dummy Al2O3
sample),
- contribution in-beam photons could be neglected
(checked by additional measurement with in-beam
filters of W,Al,Co for black resonances at 4.2, 18.8,
132 eV, 34.8 keV and by calculation from the analytical
form of this background,fitted to measured Pb spectrum.
- ambient radiation background (no beam, no sample) was
measured and normalized to the acquisition time.
The energy dependence of the beam interception factor
was not taken into account.
This work was supported by the European Commission
with the FP7 project ANDES (FP7-249671) and the French
national research program GEDEPEON.
M.M.
The value of the thermal cross section was estimated
from the normalized 241Am capture yield, using fittings
from 26.3 to 100 meV and from 0.026 eV to 0.35 eV.
The influence of the detection threshold on the
weighting function and resulting normalization was
studied.
The results for the two detectors analyzed separately
were giving consistent results.
The final adopted value of the thermal cross section
was obtained from the resonance parameters.
The extracted Westcott factor is 0.995.

x4freetext: The obtained yield with 300-keV threshold was
used for a resonance shape analysis using the R-matrix
code SAMMY in the Reich-Moore approximation, including
multiple scattering and self-shielding corrections,
and using the free gas model for Doppler broadening
with an effective temperature of 296 K. The n TOF
phase-I resolution function as given in SAMMY was used.
The neutron energy calibration was adjusted to the
4.9-eV resonance in Au using parameters from JEFF-3.1.2
resulting in an effective flight path length of
L = 184.21 +- 0.06 m. The partial gamma width was let
free for the first three large resonances.
For the negative resonance the same spin as the first
positive resonance was chosen.
The correlation factor between neutron width and gamma
width from the fit was lower than 0.25.
